            "answer_text": "The Earth is like a person suffering a mid-life crisis (hehe). She is a respectable 4.54 billion years old, but don\u2019t ask her. With an approximate 5 billion years left of her life until the Sun swallows her whole, the short answer to this question is YES. Unless something of truly cosmic proportions doesn\u2019t affect the planet, it can survive the odd meteor impact or two. Other planets do it on a daily basis, daily being in astronomical terms. The only point of concern here is that whether we puny humans would be there to witness the next One Billion years or not. This time, the short answer is NO, or at least not the way we imagine it. Think about it, in all of Earth\u2019s 4.5 G.a. (billion year) history, the earliest human-great ape common bipedal ancestor had existed a mere 9.9 M.a. (million year) ago. There is an analogy which says that if all of Earth\u2019s time was compared to a 24 hour clock[1] with 00:00 being the beginning of Earth and today being 23:59:59\u2026 then the first human ancestors (the first human mind you, not common ape but human after they separated from other hominids at around 7 M.a.) came just 2 minutes ago, at around 23:57. It only took us those 2 minutes to go from this[2] :  to this:  Imagine what we would look like in the next 5 hours 20 minutes by adding a billion more years. Maybe its us with fins or maybe its us with an afterburner. (I know the math is not right as you\u2019d have to make the clock for 5.54 billion years and not 4.54 and the percentages would change, but you get my point) There is another possibility that we might not even exist at all. The Earth has a habit of wiping the slate clean from time to time. it has done so 5 times already[3]. One time the extinction level went over 95% of all marine and 70% of all land life. Nobody knows what will happen next or will we finally have giant sentient cockroaches, but this blessed plot, this realm, this Earth will be there to be inherited.* *Terms and conditions apply. Footnotes[1] Geologic Timescale[2] Sahelanthropus tchadensis[3] Extinction event - Wikipedia",
