                "name": "Doug Freyburger",
                "href": "/profile/Doug-Freyburger"
            },
            "answer_text": "The planet itself - It will be in orbit at least until the Sun goes red giant in 5 billion years. A big chunk might even be there when the Sun shrinks to a white dwarf. Life on the planet - Main sequence stars get gradually brighter as they age. It will take about 1 billion years before our Sun gets so bright the oceans boil. At that point life is over on our planet. Our species - Every species goes extinct in under 5 million years. All of them. We will likely have post-human descendants by then - I am optimistic on this point. Either of us personally - The world record for longevity is 123. It is in no danger of being broken. No person alive today is going to break the record by much. To break the record past maybe 150 will take genetic engineering. The first person to live past 150 will probably not be born until after 2080. ",
